ement because it spans multiple agentic components—the embedding service, vector database, and LLM re-ranking—executing in sequence. Mocks would hide latency problems since in-process calls are artificially fast. Only a full pipeline test using real external services can measure actual performance. The test should execute the complete flow with a genuine query, measure total latency across multiple runs, and verify the median stays under 2 seconds with realistic query complexity and database size.\n\nThe probability distribution reflects this: Unit (0.05), Integration (0.05), System (0.15), Agentic (0.2), Workflow (0.55).\n\nReconsidering behavior 5—is it truly Workflow or System? The distinction hinges on whether this constitutes multiple agentic steps versus a system-level API test. The latency check involves real HTTP calls to the embedding service, vector database interactions, and an LLM call. Since the embedding produces deterministic outputs while the LLM introduces non-determinism, and both are tested sequentially, this qualifies as Workflow. Though there's merit to classifying it as System given the HTTP API boundary and real external service calls, the presence of multiple non-deterministic agentic elements tips it toward Workflow. Adjusting the probabilities: Unit (0.05), Integration (0.05), System (0.25), Agentic (0.15), Workflow (0.5). steps compose together and impact the overall latency. The real failure mode here is when the LLM re-ranking step becomes a bottleneck within the full pipeline—something you'd only catch by measuring latency across the entire sequence with real components, not in isolation. This requires calling the actual LLM and observing how it integrates with other services to meet the performance budget. So Workflow seems more precise than System, though there's overlap between them. Embedding is deterministic, so it's a system component rather than agentic. The LLM re-ranking step is agentic, but the overall pipeline is testing API response time at the system boundary—the composition of deterministic and agentic elements working together. I'd classify this as System-level, though there's some argument for Workflow given the multiple sequential steps involved.\n\nTo catch a real latency failure, I need the full pipeline running with actual services—embedding, vector search, LLM, and timing measurement. The minimum infrastructure is the HTTP API endpoint with real external dependencies. System testing makes the most sense here since I'm validating the API performance, not the agentic behavior in isolation.\n\nMy confidence distribution: Unit: 0.05, Integration: 0.05, System: 0.55, Agentic: 0.1, Workflow: 0.25\n\n**Behavior 5: The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.**\n\n- Minimum level: **System**\n- Justification: Mocking external services masks latency issues since in-process calls are fast. I need real HTTP calls to the embedding service, actual vector database queries, and real LLM re-ranking calls to measure true end-to-end time. This is System-level because it depends on real external API calls and network latency.\n- Test description: Execute the full HTTP API endpoint with real external services and measure total response time.\n\nRun the endpoint multiple times with realistic query complexity and database size, verifying median latency stays under 2 seconds. The latency requirement inherently demands testing against real services to validate the deadline is achievable.\n\nFor plan consistency: dimensionality detection requires the real embedding service; similarity ranking needs the actual vector database; LLM re-ranking needs a real model to verify it actually re-ranks; and the no-close-matches case needs the real database to confirm behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13373,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation